entry.title: [dPWA] Refactoring commands to remove all re-entry.
entry.content:
This change takes a set of norms that all commands have needed to

follow to maintain safety and bakes them directly into the command

system, allowing a lot of code deletion and making a variety of UAF /

reentry bugs impossible.



Specifically, this:

- Puts the base::Value::Dict directly into the command, instead of

having the command implement ToDebugValue(), which caused UAFs in

the past. This includes elevating the debug value in the 'jobs' as

well.

- Removes the OnShutdown method, and instead has the shutdown args be

provided on construction & saved in the command base class.

- Stores the callback directly into the command, guaranteeing that it

is called after the command is complete.

- Upgrades the callback commands to always provide the lock & the

debug value, allowing the 'result' value to be returned by the

callback.

- Fixes a bugs where commands scheduled before Start now have their

scheduled location saved correctly.

- Correctly reports success in command

CheckIsolatedWebAppBundleInstallabilityCommand (note that this value

isn't used for anything yet, so this is essentially a no-op change.)



Some changes required to make this work correctly:

- InstallFromInfo needed to be split into two commands to accommodate

the 'replace' version needing a different callback type. The replace

version seems only to be used by tests, so that can eventually be

deleted, but to keep this patch from exploding more I simply created

two different commands here.

- WebAppUninstallCommand can't accept a job if that job also needs the

debug value from the command. So it was refactored to construct the

jobs internally, and have explicit static naming to specify which

type of uninstall command it is.

entry.title: Improve handling of notification actions in App Shims.
entry.content:
Notification actions should be able to notify the browser process

even if the browser process hasn't tried to connect to the

notification service in the app shim process yet. Additionally,

if an app shim is launched by the OS to handle a notification

action, we need to make sure to install a UNUserNotificationCenter

delegate before the launch finishes.



To make this possible, this CL splits out what used to all be in

the constructor of MacNotificationServiceUN to now have separate

construction, mojo-bind and RequestPermission calls. This allows

app shims to create the service on startup, while only binding its

receiver and requesting permission when the browser process asks

for this.



Also uses a single MacNotificationServiceUN instance for the lifetime

of the app shim, routing notification actions through a mojo pipe

that is setup on initial connection with the browser process, rather

than using the action handler mojo pipe that is passed when the

browser process connects to the notification service.

user from interacting with the browser when these actions are triggered,

a launch screen will be shown until the actions complete allowing the

user to interact.

callback is dispatched after a timeout period to prevent the screen

from showing indefinitely.

entry.title: Allow non-opaque fenced frames to inherit select permissions.
entry.content:
For fenced frames with unpartitioned data access, they will need to use

Shared Storage in order to read and write the unpartitioned data. They

will also need to be able to call the Private Aggregation API in order

to send reports and telemetry without running the risk of introducing a

fingerprinting vector. Both of those features are permissions

policy-backed features.



Fenced frames do not currently support permissions policies, so none of

these features will be able to be enabled. The reason we disabled

permissions policies originally was to prevent cross-channel

communication from the embedder into the fenced frame. However, fenced

frames with unpartitioned data do allow for data inflow, just not data

outflow. Because of that, we can now allow permissions policies to be

enabled on non-opaque fenced frames (i.e. fenced frames not created

using Protected Audience or Shared Storage).



This CL allows fenced frames to set and inherit permissions policies.

Only Shared Storage and Private Aggregation can be turned on. All other

permissions policies will be forced off if attempted to be enabled or

inherited, and a console warning will be output for debugging purposes.

Note that fenced frames created through Protected Audience or Shared

Storage will continue to have their existing restrictions, and this CL

will not affect their behavior.



As a feature of its architecture, MPArch does not have access to

permissions policy information in its parent on the renderer side. To

give a fenced frame that access, we need to explicitly give it that

information through the fenced frame properties. This CL adds the parent

frame's parsed permissions policies and its origin to the

FencedFrameConfig and FencedFrameProperties objects. This is done

instead of just adding the PermissionsPolicy object for IPC reasons. The

parsed permissions policies and origin can be sent in an IPC message and

are the 2 pieces needed in order to reconstruct a PermissionsPolicy on

the renderer-side.



This CL also fixes an issue where container policies for fenced frame

roots were not taken into consideration when building the permissions

policy on the renderer side.



This CL explicitly does not modify any permissions policy code related

to client hints. That will be done as a follow up if and when we choose

to allow client hints in fenced frames.

entry.title: SQLite: sidestep Mac crash when acting on non-existent file
entry.content:
Chrome tries to propagate TimeMachine exclusions from the main

database file to its journal file. In some cases, the database

file doesn't exist, which causes a DCHECK. This change papers

over that by verifying the database file exists before calling

base utilities on it.



It's not clear if the existence of a -journal file without

the database file is an error case or can happen normally.

If it is an error case, then we rely on other SQLite code to

notice and error out (but not crash). If it is not an error

case, then the worst thing that will happen due to this change

is that a -journal file may not be excluded from TimeMachine.

The journal file is much smaller than the database file, so

this outcome, while not ideal, is hardly terrible.



crbug.com/25959 has the original justification for this

behavior, and in that example the journal files are less than

2% of the size of the database files.

entry.title: [3PCD][Optimization] HostIndexedContentSettings to index secondary_pattern
entry.content:
HostIndexedContentSettings contains three sets of

ContentSettingPatternSource. If the primary_pattern has a non-wildcard

host, it stores the in the

primary_host_indexed_ map. If the primary_pattern has a wildcard

hostname and the secondary_pattern does not, it stores the

pair in the

secondary_host_indexed_ map. Finally, if either both primary_pattern

and secondary_pattern contain no hostname or they both contain wildcard

hostnames, HostIndexedContentSettings stores the

ContentSettingPatternSource in the wildcard_settings_ vector.

same-document navigation in AF and PWM, meaning that this restriction

submission with a DOM_MUTATION_AFTER_XHR source, which was trusted for

all frames and not just the main frame. Meaning that we only used to

discard same-document navigation on non-main frames when the tracked

element disappeared before this and not after.



Since the order of navigation and disappearence is arbitrary, that

should be another reason supporting this change.

entry.title: ui/display: Parse DisplayID in EDID for tile properties
entry.content:
Add Tiled display topology block DisplayID extension parsing to

EdidParser.



DisplayID block with tag 0x28 (and 0x12 for the previous version which

seems to be very similar) is the Tiled display topology block. The

block, if present, contains properties of a tiled display such as

layout, size, location, etc. Though many of these properties are

available in EDID as well, tiled display toplogy block contains

information on "Tile Behavior when the only tile being transmitted",

which this CL extends EdidParser to obtain.



DisplayID is sometimes available in EDID as an extension, so this

change looks for the DisplayID extension tag, and tries to parse out

tile display information if available.

entry.content:
A token binding challenge needs to be propagated from

OAuth2AccessTokenManager::Fetcher down to MutableP02TSDelegate which

knows how to sign challenges with token binding keys.

to `CreateAccessTokenFetcher()` methods from

`OAuth2AccessTokenManager::Delegate` till

`ProfileOAuth2TokenServiceDelegate`.



All other P02TSDelegate implementations ignore this new parameter for

now as the challenge never should be set for them. We might change it

later and treat non-empty challenge as an explicit error.

entry.title: android: Estimate number of Binder service proxies installed
entry.content:
The ServiceTracingProxyProvider proxies a number of Binder services to

add trace events with binder call duration to Chrome traces. As the

platform is changing, it is important to update the proxy for better

interception.



Currently there is no easy way to find out that a new OS release or a

particular device model or OEM broke a significant number of proxies. It

seems that the best way to find this out is to process many traces from

the field (using the "Trace Processor").



This change adds a histogram to work as a "litmus test".

Since the services are proxied lazily, the code tracks the first N

attempts to install proxies (there are no retries) and records how many

succeeded among them.



I chose N=40 because in my testing 40-50 proxying attempts are made on

startup when restoring a Wikipedia page.



On my local Android OS build the number of successful proxy

installations is 11 (eleven). Not a lot.



In this local experiment the ServiceTracingProxyProvider could not find

Binder services for the following wrappers:
